<div id="review_599137580" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/599137580" />
    <a title="Shane Hall" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12464952-shane-hall"><img alt="Shane Hall" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1429211181p2/12464952.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/599137580?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shane Hall" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shane Hall" href="/user/show/12464952-shane-hall">Shane Hall</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer599137580" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer535719832416431348">An easy contender for the best fictional work I&apos;ve read. I will never give away my own personal copy. In no other novel have I seen such brilliant use of second person point of view. <br/>You are the protagonist, and like a spell, the novel convinces you, from the very start, that you are this man, looking for a job sorting the written documents of an hideous old widow&apos;s late husband. You are bothered by her loneliness, but magnetically attracted to her young niece, Aura. Her beauty convinces you to </span>
  <span id="freeText535719832416431348" style="display:none">An easy contender for the best fictional work I've read. I will never give away my own personal copy. In no other novel have I seen such brilliant use of second person point of view. <br />You are the protagonist, and like a spell, the novel convinces you, from the very start, that you are this man, looking for a job sorting the written documents of an hideous old widow's late husband. You are bothered by her loneliness, but magnetically attracted to her young niece, Aura. Her beauty convinces you to take up the job. This means you live with the two women in that odd humid house of darkness and potted plants. These women, one beautiful and one pitiful, are much more than they seem.<br />Aura is a novel that guides you with sensory details, removing your sense of control and security. When you get down to it, this is a horror novel, and it succeedes in that aspect, in a way so bloodless and subdued as to rupture you from within.<br />The plot is based on a twist that appears right at the end, and it's seriously chilling. It also inspires second readings, into the clues that were laid out before you. Spoiling this surprise will spoil the entire novel.<br />Dive into it, don't read any more about it than you have to, and surrender to the spell.</span>
  <a data-text-id="535719832416431348" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


