<div id="review_72038721" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/72038721" />
    <a title="Eldonfoil TH*E Whatever Champion" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2422096-eldonfoil-th-e-whatever-champion"><img alt="Eldonfoil TH*E Whatever Champion" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616206760p2/2422096.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/72038721?book_show_action=true">Sep 21, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eldonfoil TH*E Whatever Champion" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eldonfoil TH*E Whatever Champion" href="/user/show/2422096-eldonfoil-th-e-whatever-champion">Eldonfoil TH*E Whatever Champion</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2422096-eldonfoil-th-e-whatever-champion?shelf=latin-american">latin-american</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer72038721" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13025442587427954518">Creepy and frightening? Reminiscent of Poe? On a pendulum with Poe on one end and your favorite Stephen King ordeal on the other, I&apos;d put Aura somewhere in the middle----which is to say, putting it on par with Poe is like comparing cherries to persimmons. The levels of tension and writing are not equivalent.<br/><br/>How many more books can I read that employ the basic device of mistaken, switched, transferred, or double identity?????---in all its forms! Someone needs to write a book with 332 characters w</span>
  <span id="freeText13025442587427954518" style="display:none">Creepy and frightening? Reminiscent of Poe? On a pendulum with Poe on one end and your favorite Stephen King ordeal on the other, I'd put Aura somewhere in the middle----which is to say, putting it on par with Poe is like comparing cherries to persimmons. The levels of tension and writing are not equivalent.<br /><br />How many more books can I read that employ the basic device of mistaken, switched, transferred, or double identity?????---in all its forms! Someone needs to write a book with 332 characters who are really all the same (revealed at the end, of course). At least Aura did not use the ploy to make some grand comment on 'consciousness' and 'knowing.' After reading literary giants like Pamuk, Cortazar, and Fuentes go back to this trick over and over again, I start to feel as if I'm repeatedly watching cheap movies like Abre tus Ojos. (They all use the same handy-dandy trick of mixing and matching tenses and points of view as well.)<br /><br />This is not a bad story, but it's not the haunting, shimmering fairy tale some make it out to be. Really, it's rather bland and simple, and that's not due to "lost in translation."<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13025442587427954518" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


